ting its modernity from the Constitutional Revolution of 1905 up to and beyond the Islamic Revolution of 1979. By focusing on marriage as the central metaphor through which both law and fiction read gender, Motlagh critically engages and highlights the difficulties that arise as gender norms and laws change over time. She examines the recurrent foregrounding of marriage at five critical periods of legal reform, documenting how texts were understood both at first publication and as their importance changed over time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aLaw and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxIran. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx20th centuryxIran. 0aMarriage in literature. 0aPersian fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aPersian literaturexSocial aspectsxIran. 0aRealism in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxIran. 0aWomen's rightsxIran. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804778183zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778183423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778183.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles